<DOC><DOCNO> AP891222-0288 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-89 1853EST</FILEID><FIRST>u f BC-BusinessHighlights     12-22 0848</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Business Highlights,0889</SECOND><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Orders to U.S. factories for durable goodsposted a 5.1 percent gain in November, the sharpest increase in ayear, the government said. Analysts said the report suggested theeconomy can avoid a recession.   The Commerce Department said Friday that orders for durablegoods _ costly items expected to last at least three years _increased to a seasonally adjusted $130.7 billion last month afterdropping 0.7 percent in October and 1.2 percent in September.   The gain in orders was spread through all categories and was thelargest since a 7.4 percent jump last December. It averted thefirst three-month decline since 1986.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Senate Ethics Committee said it willformally investigate five senators who intervened with bankingregulators on behalf of a wealthy contributor whose huge savingsand loan was failing.   The senators all have denied wrongdoing and said they welcomedthe announcement.   The ethics panel said Friday it will probe the activities ofMajority Whip Alan Cranston, D-Calif.; Banking Committee ChairmanDonald W. Riegle, Jr., D-Mich.; John McCain, R-Ariz.; DennisDeConcini, D-Ariz., and John Glenn, D-Ohio.</TEXT><DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Bank of New England Corp., which expects heavylosses due to bad real estate loans, has rescinded a common stockdividend declared last month.   The announcement Friday came one week after Bank of New Englandsaid it would boost its loan reserves above $1 billion and that itexpected a ``substantial'' loss for the year. The bank struggledamid a regional real estate slump.</TEXT><DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Smithkline Beecham PLC, a major internationalpharmaceutical company, has agreed to sell its U.S. and Canadianhousehold products businesses to a West German company for $107million in cash.   Smithkline said Friday the sale to Joh. A. Benckiser GmbH isconsistent with its strategy of focusing on internationalhealthcare following the merger of Smithkline Beckman Corp. withBeecham Group PLC earlier this year.   Household products included in the sale are Calgon, a leadingU.S. bath additive, Cling Free, a fabric softener used in driers,and Delicare, a detergent for delicate products.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Columbia Pictures Entertainment Inc. has putMcCann-Erickson Worldwide in charge of placing domestic advertisingfor both its Columbia Pictures and Tri-Star Pictures movies.   The decision Friday could mean an extra $70 million to $75million in annual billings for the giant New York-based agency,which had previously held the assignment for placing only theColumbia Pictures ads.   The loser is ACandamp;R Advertising, a unit of Britain's Saatchi andamp;Saatchi Co. PLC which had been responsible for placing theTri-State Pictures advertising.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Ford Motor Co. intends to sell $1.55 billionin debt securities to pay for its recent acquisition of Associates,the nation's third-largest independent finance company, accordingto documents.   In a registration statement filed Friday with the Securities andExchange Commission, Ford said it is seeking to issue the debtsecurities through Ford Holdings Inc., a subsidiary formed inSeptember to acquire Associates.   The debt securities will be sold ``to reduce short-term debt,including borrowings to fund the acquisition of Associates,''according to the registration statement.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A federal judge has unsealed confidentialcorporate documents in a lawsuit against Mobil Oil Corp. butwithheld the order when lawyers for the oil giant said they wouldappeal.   The company is fighting to prevent the disclosure of thedocuments _ reports on environmental conditions at its chemicaldivision plants _ because it says they are self-criticalevaluations.   Disclosing such reports would have a chilling effect on acompany's efforts to be candid about its operations, Mobil arguedFriday.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Bush administration plans to lift acongressional ban on government loans to Iraq, a move expected toantagonize lawmakers critical of Iraq's human rights abuses andcredit problems.   Officials say President Bush will exercise his right to lift theban, imposed by Congress several months ago, on grounds of U.S.national interests. The officials said the move is expected withinseveral weeks.   U.S. oil companies and other businesses have exerted heavypressure on the administration to broaden trade ties with Iraqsince the 1988 end of its ruinous 8-year war with Iran.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Westinghouse Electric Corp. is consideringappealing for an increase in the $3.9 million bonus it won forrunning the Savannah River nuclear weapons plant despite safetylapses such as workers sleeping on the job, an Energy Departmentofficial said.   Westinghouse officials at the South Carolina plant, however,said Friday there were no plans to appeal.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   The stock market worked its way higher in quiet preholidaytrading Friday. The Dow Jones industrial average climbed 20.26points to 2,711.39, cutting its loss for the week to 28.16 points.   The dollar tumbled in abbreviated pre-Christmas foreign-exchangetrading.   Bond prices fell.   Orange juice futures prices fell sharply; heating oil futuresposted fresh gains as the nation's record-setting cold spellcontinued; precious metals advanced; livestock and meat futureswere mixed; and grains and soybeans were mixed.</TEXT></DOC>